# Kill the redis.subscriber.error Storm (102M rows)

## Question

ClickHouse holds 102,052,982 `redis.subscriber.error` rows — 99.78% of the
entire OTEL table, poisoning the telemetry sink the observer/anomaly work
depends on. Find the erroring subscriber (system-bus), fix the root cause,
and decide cleanup (drop the storm partition-wise vs let 180d TTL eat it).
Receipts from the ingress inventory.

## Answer

The gateway Redis retry loop leaked one subscriber/command client pair per
manual retry. Old ioredis clients kept reconnecting and each subscriber emitted
an uncapped `redis.subscriber.error` row. The code fix disposes failed pairs,
rebinds the message store on recovery, bounds shutdown cleanup, and emits
bounded detail-plus-summary telemetry.

ClickHouse was cleaned with partition-scoped `ALTER DELETE` mutations for
`202607` and `202606`. Both mutations completed. Storm rows fell from
102,052,982 to 0; active table storage fell from 3.76 GiB to 26.41 MiB. All 141
non-storm `source, action` groups survived the cleanup with zero count
decreases at the preservation cutoff.

Full receipt: [Kill the storm, clean the debris](../../tasks/kill-redis-error-storm.svx).

## Resolution (2026-07-13)

Root cause fixed in gateway redis channel; error-emission budget added (cap + summary row — no future storms). ClickHouse debris cleaned: final storm query 0 rows, non-storm telemetry preserved. Unblocks build-observer-telemetry-watch.
